<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,603,2085]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">
Acaulescent perennial herb sometimes dividing at the crown. Roots thick, thong-like, to 370 × 
<quantity box="[1202,1271,603,629]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
. Rhizome stout, crown thick, woody, silky-woolly. Leaves radical, spreading, ovate to suborbicular, blade 11–23 × 
<quantity box="[1259,1375,638,664]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.7" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="cm" value="17.0" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="12.0">12–22 cm</quantity>
, upper surface dark green, pilose; lower surface pale greenish-white, tomentose, white-felted, midrib and ca. 5 side nerves strongly raised; margins entire to repand with short, hornlike projections where tertiary veins meet margin, secondary veins looping, apex rounded to obtuse, base cordate, lobes often imbricate with age. Petiole terete, tomentose-villose, up to 190 × 
<quantity box="[282,352,776,803]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="4.0">4 mm</quantity>
. Scapes ebracteate, 1–7 from crown, 150–450 × 
<quantity box="[918,1037,776,803]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.25" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="2.25" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.0">2–2.5 mm</quantity>
, villose to tomentose, hairs whitish. Involucre campanulate, ca. 20 × 
<quantity box="[505,587,811,837]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
; bracts lanceolate 3–17 × 
<quantity box="[881,1019,811,838]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="1.0" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.5">0.5–1.5 mm</quantity>
, white-villose outside, imbricate, 3–4- seriate. Capitula erect, radiate, heterogamous, 30–50(–70) mm across the spreading rays. Florets bilabiate, minute purple clavate glands occasional; outer series of female florets white, tube 
<quantity box="[1003,1120,880,907]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.75" metricValueMax="6.5" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="5.75" valueMax="6.5" valueMin="5.0">5–6.5 mm</quantity>
long, mouth white or green, staminodes 5, filamentous, outer limb rarely tinged pink below, 12–18 × 
<quantity box="[965,1061,915,941]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4 mm</quantity>
, inner limbs 0.5 × 
<quantity box="[1277,1381,915,942]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="0.25">0.25 mm</quantity>
; inner female florets white, tube 
<quantity box="[443,575,949,976]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.75" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="7.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="8.75" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="7.5">7.5–10 mm</quantity>
long, outer limb 2–2.5 × 
<quantity box="[882,953,950,976]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
, inner limbs 1–2 × 
<quantity box="[1187,1279,949,976]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
, staminodes 5, filamentous; disc florets hermaphrodite, white, tube 
<quantity box="[743,875,984,1011]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.25" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="8.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="9.25" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="8.5">8.5–10 mm</quantity>
long, limbs 2.5–4 × 
<quantity box="[1124,1245,984,1011]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="1.75" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.5">1.5–2 mm</quantity>
; anthers sagittate, tailed, yellow, pollen white. Pappus bristles barbellate, whitish. Cypselae 
<quantity box="[972,1094,1019,1045]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10–12 mm</quantity>
long, elliptic, 3–6-ribbed, beak 
<quantity box="[136,229,1054,1080]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="mm" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4 mm</quantity>
long, puberulous along length, hairs filiform, pointed. Chromosome number: unknown. (
<figureCitation box="[1229,1300,1053,1080]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,229,1918,1940]" captionTargetBox="[223,1390,195,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[197,1390,187,1890]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. A–I. Gerbera sylvicola I.M.Johnson, N.R.Crouch &amp; T.J.Edwards (holotype: iLembe District, KwaZulu-Natal, I. Johnson, N. Crouch &amp; D. Styles 1524, BNRH). A. Flowering plant, habit. B. Cordate leaf. C. Outer ray floret, half the pappus cut away. D. Disc floret, half the pappus cut away. E. Inner ray floret, half the pappus cut away. F. Ray floret tube opened to show staminodes. G. Cypsela. H. Involucral bracts. I. Pilose adaxial leaf surface, margin with short, horn-like projection. Scales A–B: 20 mm; C–E: 5 mm; F: 2 mm; G: 5 mm; H: 5 mm; I: 1 mm. Illustration by S.M. Burrows." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5153733" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5153733/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Figs 1</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation box="[1335,1352,1054,1080]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[142,1446,190,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[142,1446,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gerbera sylvicola. A. Habit showing discolorous, spreading leaves with blades held horizontal, bases cordate, often imbricate. B. Capitulum, disc florets mature, apical view. C. Capitulum lateral view, involucre white-villose. D. Ray florets, green tube mouths and maximally exerted styles. E. Infructescence, whitish pappus on beaked cypselae. F. Forest habitat at type locality. Scales A: 10 cm; B–E: 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5153735" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5153735/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="230" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,603,2085]" box="[189,1299,1088,1115]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,279,1088,1114]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Biology</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="I. M. Johnson, N. R. Crouch &amp; T. J. Edwards" authorityYear="2014" box="[315,517,1088,1114]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvicola">
<emphasis box="[315,517,1088,1114]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Gerbera sylvicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
flowers throughout the year, mainly between September and January.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,603,2085]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,281,1122,1148]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Habitat</emphasis>
:—All recorded populations occur on Natal Group Sandstone; on eastern and southern aspects at elevations of 
<quantity box="[167,311,1157,1184]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.35" metricValueMax="11.2" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" unit="m" value="735.0" valueMax="1120.0" valueMin="350.0">350–1120 m</quantity>
. Plants 
<taxonomicName box="[399,506,1157,1184]" form="part" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" rank="form">form part</taxonomicName>
of the understory on steeply sloping terrain, growing in the full shade of the forest. Individuals often occur in shallow soil pockets between boulders (
<figureCitation box="[893,963,1192,1218]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[142,1446,190,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[142,1446,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gerbera sylvicola. A. Habit showing discolorous, spreading leaves with blades held horizontal, bases cordate, often imbricate. B. Capitulum, disc florets mature, apical view. C. Capitulum lateral view, involucre white-villose. D. Ray florets, green tube mouths and maximally exerted styles. E. Infructescence, whitish pappus on beaked cypselae. F. Forest habitat at type locality. Scales A: 10 cm; B–E: 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5153735" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5153735/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), and can 
<taxonomicName box="[1083,1201,1192,1218]" form="large" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" rank="form">form large</taxonomicName>
colonies. Populations sometimes occur on the ecotone between Southern Mistbelt Forest (FOz 3) and Scarp Forest (FOz 5) (
<bibRefCitation author="Rutherford, M. C. &amp; Powrie, L. W. &amp; Lotter, M. C. &amp; Von Maltitz, G. P. &amp; Euston-Brown, D. I. W. &amp; Matthews, W. S. &amp; Dobson, L. &amp; McKenzie, B." pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="584 - 614" refId="ref3510" refString="Rutherford, M. C., Powrie, L. W., Lotter, M. C., Von Maltitz, G. P., Euston-Brown, D. I. W., Matthews, W. S., Dobson, L. &amp; McKenzie, B. (2006) Afrotemperate, Subtropical and Azonal Forests. In: Mucina, L. &amp; Rutherford, M. C. (eds), The vegetation of South Africa, Lesotho and Swaziland. Strelitzia 19: 584 - 614." type="journal article" year="2006">
Rutherford 
<emphasis box="[1396,1445,1227,1253]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
), and within Scarp Forest. Associated flora includes 
<taxonomicName authority="(Haworth 1831: 415) Bos (1992: 3)" authorityName="Bos" authorityPageNumber="3" authorityYear="1992" baseAuthorityName="Haworth" baseAuthorityPageNumber="415" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[787,1446,1261,1288]" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Dracaena" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aletriformis">
<emphasis box="[787,1038,1261,1287]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Dracaena aletriformis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Haworth, A. H." box="[1053,1275,1261,1288]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="414 - 424" refId="ref3003" refString="Haworth, A. H. (1831) Mr. Haworth's thirteenth Decade of New Succulent Plants. The Philosophical Magazine or Annals of Chemistry, Mathematics, Astronomy, Natural History, and General Science 2 nd Ser. 10: 414 - 424." type="book chapter" year="1831">Haworth 1831: 415</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Bos, J. J." box="[1290,1446,1262,1288]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref2707" refString="Bos, J. J. (1992) Dracaena. In: Leistner, O. A. (ed.) Flora of southern Africa 5 (3). National Botanical Institute, Pretoria, pp. 1 - 4." type="book chapter" year="1992">Bos (1992: 3)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hooker (1868" authorityName="Hooker" authorityYear="1868" box="[136,542,1296,1322]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sutherlandii">
<emphasis box="[136,372,1296,1322]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Begonia sutherlandii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hooker, J. D." box="[380,542,1296,1322]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" refId="ref3105" refString="Hooker, J. D. (1868) Begonia sutherlandi. Dr. Sutherland's Begonia. Curtis's Botanical Magazine 3 rd Series 94: t. 5689." type="book" year="1868">Hooker (1868</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
: t. 5689), 
<taxonomicName authority="(Linnaeus 1759: 870) Palisot de Beauvois (1812: 168)" authorityName="Palisot de Beauvois" authorityPageNumber="168" authorityYear="1812" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityPageNumber="870" baseAuthorityYear="1759" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Oplismenus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hirtellus">
<emphasis box="[656,889,1296,1322]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Oplismenus hirtellus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." box="[905,1132,1296,1323]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="825 - 1384" refId="ref3308" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1759) Systema naturae per regna tria naturae: secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis, ed. 10, vol. 2. L. Salvius, Stockholm, 825 - 1384 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 559" type="book chapter" year="1759">Linnaeus 1759: 870</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Palisot de Beauvois, A. M. F. J." pageId="1" pageNumber="230" refId="ref3443" refString="Palisot de Beauvois, A. M. F. J. (1812) Essai d'une nouvelle agrostographie, ou, Nouveaux genres des gramine ' es: avec figures repre ' sentant les caracte`res de tous les genres. Chez L'auteur, Paris, 182 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 474" type="book" year="1812">Palisot de Beauvois (1812: 168)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Thunberg 1794: 63) Jacques (1862: 345)" authorityName="Jacques" authorityPageNumber="345" authorityYear="1862" baseAuthorityName="Thunberg" baseAuthorityPageNumber="63" baseAuthorityYear="1794" box="[242,990,1331,1358]" class="Liliopsida" family="Asparagaceae" genus="Chlorophytum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="comosum">
<emphasis box="[242,516,1331,1357]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Chlorophytum comosum</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Thunberg, C. P." box="[530,747,1331,1358]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" refId="ref3736" refString="Thunberg, C. P. (1794) Prodromus plantarum Capensium, quas in promontorio Bonae Spei Africes, annis 1772 - 1775, collegit Carol. Pet. Thunberg. Part 1. Upsala, J. Edman, 83 pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 84" type="book" year="1794">Thunberg 1794: 63</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Jacques, H. A." box="[762,990,1331,1358]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="343 - 345" refId="ref3134" refString="Jacques, H. A. (1862) Notes sur les plantes nouvelles, rares ou peu connues. Journal de la Societe Imperiale et Centrale d'Horticulture 8: 343 - 345." type="journal article" year="1862">Jacques (1862: 345)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="230" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,603,2085]" box="[189,1434,1365,1392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,332,1365,1391]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Distribution</emphasis>
:—Recorded from three forests in north-central 
<collectingRegion box="[856,1031,1365,1391]" country="South Africa" name="KwaZulu-Natal" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">KwaZulu-Natal</collectingRegion>
, essentially within Zululand (
<figureCitation box="[1353,1419,1365,1392]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[136,229,925,947]" captionText="FIGURE 3. Known distribution of Gerbera sylvicola in South Africa." pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,603,2085]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,661,1400,1426]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Diagnostic characters and relationships</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="I. M. Johnson, N. R. Crouch &amp; T. J. Edwards" authorityYear="2014" box="[696,898,1400,1426]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvicola">
<emphasis box="[696,898,1400,1426]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Gerbera sylvicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows a unique combination of characters within the genus (
<tableCitation box="[260,345,1435,1461]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,158,184]" captionText="TABLE 1. Main diagnostic characters between G. sylvicola, G. ambigua (Hilliard 1977, 1994), G. kraussii (Hilliard 1977, 1994) and G. cordata (Hansen 1985a, 1990)." pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Table 1</tableCitation>
). It is one of only two South African species adapted to low light conditions on forest floors, the other being 
<taxonomicName authority="(Thunberg 1800: 154) Lessing (1830: 297)" authorityName="Lessing" authorityPageNumber="297" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Thunberg" baseAuthorityPageNumber="154" baseAuthorityYear="1800" box="[273,891,1469,1496]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordata">
<emphasis box="[273,395,1469,1496]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. cordata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Thunberg, C. P." box="[411,645,1469,1496]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" refId="ref3796" refString="Thunberg, C. P. (1800) Prodromus plantarum Capensium, quas in promontorio Bonae Spei Africes, annis 1772 - 1775, collegit Carol. Pet. Thunberg. Part 2. Upsala, J. Edman, 191 pp." type="book" year="1800">Thunberg 1800: 154</bibRefCitation>
) 
<bibRefCitation author="Lessing, C. F." box="[662,891,1469,1496]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="237 - 298" refId="ref3268" refString="Lessing, C. F. (1830) De synanthereis Herbarii Regii Berolinensis. Linnaea 5: 237 - 298." type="journal article" year="1830">Lessing (1830: 297)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
which is not only geographically well separated, occurring in the forests of the Eastern and 
<collectingRegion box="[639,798,1504,1531]" country="South Africa" name="Western Cape" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Western Cape</collectingRegion>
Provinces, but is placed in the separate section 
<emphasis box="[1363,1391,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G.</emphasis>
sect. 
<taxonomicName authority="Lessing (1830: 296)" authorityName="Lessing" authorityPageNumber="296" authorityYear="1830" box="[136,514,1539,1566]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Piloselloides" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[136,281,1539,1565]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Piloselloides</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lessing, C. F." box="[288,514,1539,1566]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="237 - 298" refId="ref3268" refString="Lessing, C. F. (1830) De synanthereis Herbarii Regii Berolinensis. Linnaea 5: 237 - 298." type="journal article" year="1830">Lessing (1830: 296)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
based on the scape 
<taxonomicName box="[737,839,1539,1565]" form="and" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" rank="form">form and</taxonomicName>
cypsela characters. Although at first sight 
<taxonomicName authorityName="I. M. Johnson, N. R. Crouch &amp; T. J. Edwards" authorityYear="2014" box="[1317,1452,1539,1565]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvicola">
<emphasis box="[1317,1452,1539,1565]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. sylvicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lessing" authorityYear="1830" baseAuthorityName="Thunberg" baseAuthorityYear="1800" box="[422,541,1573,1600]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cordata">
<emphasis box="[422,541,1573,1600]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. cordata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it differs in possessing cypselae with shorter beaks (
<tableCitation box="[1124,1207,1573,1600]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,158,184]" captionText="TABLE 1. Main diagnostic characters between G. sylvicola, G. ambigua (Hilliard 1977, 1994), G. kraussii (Hilliard 1977, 1994) and G. cordata (Hansen 1985a, 1990)." pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Table 1</tableCitation>
), annuli lacking clubshaped hairs, and the cypsela lacking inflated, apiculate hairs (
<bibRefCitation author="Hansen, H. V." box="[827,979,1608,1634]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="469 - 485" refId="ref2915" refString="Hansen, H. V. (1990) Phylogenetic studies in the Gerbera - complex (Compositae, tribe Mutisieae, subtribe Mutisiinae). Nordic Journal of Botany 9: 469 - 485. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1756 - 1051.1990. tb 00537. x" type="journal article" year="1990">Hansen 1990</bibRefCitation>
). The scapes do not widen below the head, and its leaves are pilose above and not scabrid, without rufous hairs below. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="I. M. Johnson, N. R. Crouch &amp; T. J. Edwards" authorityYear="2014" box="[980,1181,1643,1669]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvicola">
<emphasis box="[980,1181,1643,1669]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Gerbera sylvicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1329,1452,1643,1669]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kraussii">
<emphasis box="[1329,1452,1643,1669]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. kraussii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its leaf base never contracting into a winged petiole, in its pappus that is whitish rather than violet-purple, and in its upper leaf surface being pilose rather than velvety pubescent. It differs from both 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1081,1213,1712,1738]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambigua">
<emphasis box="[1081,1213,1712,1738]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. ambigua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1267,1390,1712,1738]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kraussii">
<emphasis box="[1267,1390,1712,1738]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. kraussii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its forested niche preferences: 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[440,571,1747,1773]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambigua">
<emphasis box="[440,571,1747,1773]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. ambigua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tolerates at most open woodland situations and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1097,1218,1747,1773]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kraussii">
<emphasis box="[1097,1218,1747,1773]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. kraussii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only open grassland. Presentation by the new species of strongly raised veins below distinguishes it from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hilliard 1977)" baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1071,1447,1781,1808]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambigua">
<emphasis box="[1071,1270,1781,1807]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Gerbera ambigua</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hilliard, O. M." box="[1284,1439,1781,1808]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" refId="ref3050" refString="Hilliard, O. M. (1977) Compositae in Natal. University of Natal Press, Pietermaritzburg, 659 pp." type="book" year="1977">Hilliard 1977</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It further differs in holding the blades of its much larger leaves more or less horizontal rather than angled (
<figureCitation box="[1322,1390,1816,1842]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[136,229,1919,1941]" captionTargetBox="[142,1446,190,1895]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[142,1446,190,1895]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Gerbera sylvicola. A. Habit showing discolorous, spreading leaves with blades held horizontal, bases cordate, often imbricate. B. Capitulum, disc florets mature, apical view. C. Capitulum lateral view, involucre white-villose. D. Ray florets, green tube mouths and maximally exerted styles. E. Infructescence, whitish pappus on beaked cypselae. F. Forest habitat at type locality. Scales A: 10 cm; B–E: 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5153735" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5153735/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), and in lacking underground stolons. Significantly, none of the synonyms included in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1033,1156,1851,1877]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="kraussii">
<emphasis box="[1033,1156,1851,1877]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. kraussii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1192,1323,1851,1877]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambigua">
<emphasis box="[1192,1323,1851,1877]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. ambigua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hilliard, O. M." pageId="1" pageNumber="230" refId="ref3050" refString="Hilliard, O. M. (1977) Compositae in Natal. University of Natal Press, Pietermaritzburg, 659 pp." type="book" year="1977">Hilliard (1977)</bibRefCitation>
or 
<bibRefCitation author="Hansen, H. V." box="[246,423,1885,1912]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="5 - 36" refId="ref2820" refString="Hansen, H. V. (1985 a) A taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbera (Compositae, Mutisieae) sections Gerbera, Parva, Piloselloides (in Africa), and Lasiopus. Opera Botanica 78: 5 - 36." type="journal article" year="1985">Hansen (1985a)</bibRefCitation>
shows the combination of characters present in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="I. M. Johnson, N. R. Crouch &amp; T. J. Edwards" authorityYear="2014" box="[954,1087,1885,1912]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sylvicola">
<emphasis box="[954,1087,1885,1912]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. sylvicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Particular mention is here made of 
<taxonomicName authority="Thellung (1923: 452)" authorityName="Thellung" authorityPageNumber="452" authorityYear="1923" box="[165,725,1920,1947]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="ambigua" variety="cardiobasis">
<emphasis box="[165,297,1920,1946]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. ambigua</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[350,480,1920,1946]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">cardiobasis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Thellung, A." box="[485,725,1920,1947]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="440 - 456" refId="ref3652" refString="Thellung, A. (1923) Beitrage zur Kenntnis der afrikanischen Flora (XXXI) herausgegeben von H. Schinz. Compositae. Vierteljahrsschrift der Naturforschenden Gesellschaft in Zurich 68: 440 - 456." type="journal article" year="1923">Thellung (1923: 452)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, synonymised by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hansen, H. V." box="[924,1101,1920,1947]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" pagination="5 - 36" refId="ref2820" refString="Hansen, H. V. (1985 a) A taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbera (Compositae, Mutisieae) sections Gerbera, Parva, Piloselloides (in Africa), and Lasiopus. Opera Botanica 78: 5 - 36." type="journal article" year="1985">Hansen (1985a)</bibRefCitation>
with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hilliard" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[1163,1294,1920,1946]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ambigua">
<emphasis box="[1163,1294,1920,1946]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. ambigua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, an altogether smaller plant of damp coastal grasslands in Pondoland. Its leaves are more leathery, with cordate bases that are never imbricate. Further, the cypselae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thellung" authorityYear="1923" box="[526,843,1989,2016]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Gerbera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="variety" species="ambigua" variety="cardiobasis">
<emphasis box="[526,658,1989,2016]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">G. ambigua</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[713,843,1989,2015]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">cardiobasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bear a purple-violet rather than whitish pappus. These and further distinctions may be found in 
<tableCitation box="[592,676,2024,2050]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[136,229,158,184]" captionText="TABLE 1. Main diagnostic characters between G. sylvicola, G. ambigua (Hilliard 1977, 1994), G. kraussii (Hilliard 1977, 1994) and G. cordata (Hansen 1985a, 1990)." pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,758,2059,2085]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[136,1452,603,2085]" box="[189,758,2059,2085]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,318,2059,2085]" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Etymology</emphasis>
:— 
<emphasis box="[354,457,2059,2085]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="230">Sylvicola</emphasis>
= inhabitant of the woods.
</paragraph>
